{{Infobox language |name=Zurg |altname=Kufra |states=[[Libya]] |region=[[Kufra District]] |extinct=? |familycolor=Afro-Asiatic |fam2=[[Berber languages|Berber]] |fam3=[[Eastern Berber languages|Eastern]] |iso3=none |glotto=none }} '''Zurg''', or '''Kufra''', is reportedly an extinct [[Berber languages|Berber]] language formerly spoken in the town of [[Kufra]] in southeastern [[Libya]].<ref>Blench (2001) [http://www.rogerblench.info/Language/Afroasiatic/Berber/Origini%20paper%20full%20text.pdf "Types of language spread and their archaeological correlates: the example of Berber"], ''Origini'' XXIII, p. 186. Retrieved 2015 October 26.</ref> No data seems to be attested for it, and it is described by Benkato (2017) as a "ghost language" that may never have existed<ref>https://orientalberber.wordpress.com/2017/09/16/ghost-languages/</ref>.
